# NestJS spec setup

Follow [`setup-administrative-workspace.command.spec.ts`](src/commands/setup-administrative-workspace.command.spec.ts) and [`conversations.controller.spec.ts`](src/conversations/conversations.controller.spec.ts).

## Bootstrap

- Import `ConfigModule.forRoot()` and `PrismaModule` only.
- Use `providers: []` — do not register application services in the Nest module.
- Call `createTestApp(module)`, then `prismaService = app.get(PrismaService)`.
- Use `Factory.createStrategy(prismaService)` for test data.
- Reset with `resetDb(prismaService)` in `afterEach`.

## Construct dependencies manually

Build the graph with `new`, passing `prismaService` (or other already-constructed deps):

```typescript
const roleService = new RoleService();
const conversationsService = new ConversationsService(prismaService);
const teammatesService = new TeammatesService(prismaService);
const permissionService = new PermissionService(prismaService, roleService);

controller = new ConversationsController(
  conversationsService,
  teammatesService,
  permissionService,
);
```

## Avoid

- Listing service classes in `providers: [ConversationsService, TeammatesService, ...]`
- Two-phase module compiles just to wire `useValue` providers
- `TestControllerModuleWithAuthUser` when testing controller/service logic directly

## Invoke the unit under test directly

Call methods on the manually constructed instance (e.g. `controller.createDirectMessage(...)`). Assert thrown Nest exceptions with `rejects.toThrow(ForbiddenException)`.

## HTTP / auth guard tests

Use `TestControllerModuleWithAuthUser` + `supertest` only when the test specifically covers routing, guards, or status codes that require the HTTP layer (e.g. 401 without a token). For business logic and permission checks, prefer direct method calls.
